Portuguese

[edit]

Etymology

[edit]

  • (Brazil) IPA(key): /miˈma(ʁ)/ [miˈma(h)]

Verb

[edit]

mimar (first-person singular present mimo, first-person singular preterite mimei, past participle mimado)

  1. to pamper; to spoil (to treat with excessive care, to indulge)
    Synonym: paparicar

Serbo-Croatian

[edit]

Etymology

[edit]

From Ottoman Turkish معمار (mimar), from Arabic مِعْمَار (miʕmār).

Pronunciation

[edit]
  • IPA(key): /mǐmaːr/
  • Hyphenation: mi‧mar

Noun

[edit]

mìmār m anim (Cyrillic spelling мѝма̄р)

  1. architect
  2. builder

Declension

[edit]
Declension of mimar
singular plural
nominative mimar mimari
genitive mimara mimara
dative mimaru mimarima
accusative mimara mimare
vocative mimaru mimari
locative mimaru mimarima
instrumental mimarom mimarima

Related terms

[edit]
  • nèimār

Spanish

[edit]

Etymology

[edit]

From mimo +‎ -ar.

Pronunciation

[edit]
  • IPA(key): /miˈmaɾ/ [miˈmaɾ]
  • Rhymes: -aɾ
  • Syllabification: mi‧mar

Verb

[edit]

mimar (first-person singular present mimo, first-person singular preterite mimé, past participle mimado)

  1. (transitive) to pamper
  2. (transitive) to look after

Turkish

[edit]

Etymology

[edit]

Inherited from Ottoman Turkish معمار (mi'mâr), from Arabic مِعْمَار (miʕmār).

Pronunciation

[edit]
  • IPA(key): /miːmɑr/
  • Audio:(file)

Noun

[edit]

mimar (definite accusative mimarı, plural mimarlar)

  1. architect
